[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex Â· **Phase:** Regulated Â· **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on care-journey complexity, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, integration depth across systems, and human-care-manager overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Eleanor is 67. Three weeks ago, she was sitting in her primary care physician's office for her annual physical when the doctor felt something firm in her left breast that the doctor did not like the feel of. The doctor was kind about it but also visibly thinking, in the way that experienced clinicians think when they have already had this conversation many times before, that this would need imaging quickly. The doctor put in an order for a diagnostic mammogram and an ultrasound and gave Eleanor a sticky note with a phone number for the imaging center. The doctor said the imaging center would call her to schedule, that she should also expect a call from a nurse navigator, and that they would talk again after the imaging results were back. Eleanor left the office holding the sticky note. She drove home. She did not call anyone. She stared at the phone for three days before the imaging center called her, and when they did call her, she scheduled the soonest available appointment, which was nine days out because the imaging center is busy and Eleanor's insurance required a specific facility she had to drive forty-five minutes to reach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happened next is the story that approximately every patient with a serious diagnosis lives through, and it is the story this recipe exists to make less awful. The mammogram was abnormal. The ultrasound was abnormal. The radiologist recommended a stereotactic biopsy. The biopsy showed invasive ductal carcinoma. The biopsy report went to her primary care physician, who called Eleanor and told her on a Wednesday afternoon at 4:15 PM, two minutes before the doctor's office closed for the day, that she had breast cancer and that they were going to refer her to a breast surgeon and to a medical oncologist and that she would also probably see a radiation oncologist and that she should also get a genetic counseling consultation and that they would also need to do staging imaging and that she was being added to the tumor board for review next Tuesday and that someone from the cancer center would call her to coordinate. The phone call lasted seven minutes. Eleanor wrote down approximately four things on the back of an envelope. She hung up the phone and sat at her kitchen table for an hour and a half and could not remember most of what the doctor had said.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What followed, in the next eleven weeks, was a sequence of approximately twenty-four appointments, fourteen phone calls, six different patient portals (one for the imaging center, one for the cancer center, one for her primary care, one for the surgeon's separate practice, one for the genetic counselor, one for the lab), three different EHR systems she had to log into to view results, two prior-authorization fights with her insurance, one prior-authorization fight that actually delayed her treatment by eleven days, one new-patient packet at every new specialist that asked her to write down her medication list and her surgical history again, four conflicting appointment-reminder messages she received about a single appointment that had been rescheduled twice, one appointment she missed because the rescheduled time had not made it into the system she actually checked, one referral that fell into a gap between two practices and never got booked at all (she did not realize this until six weeks later when the doctor asked why she had not seen the genetic counselor yet), three results she found out about by checking her portal at midnight rather than from a clinician calling her, two questions about her diagnosis she sat with for two weeks because she did not know which doctor to ask, and a steady, grinding, exhausting low-grade panic about whether she was missing something, doing the wrong thing, or falling through cracks she could not see.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Eleanor's husband, who used to be a project manager before he retired, started keeping a spreadsheet. The spreadsheet had columns for Doctor, Specialty, Practice, Date, Type of Visit, Address, Phone Number, Reason, What They Said, Follow-up Needed, and Done. By week four the spreadsheet had thirty-seven rows. By week eight it had sixty-one. The spreadsheet was, for Eleanor and her husband, the operating system of her cancer treatment, because no operating system was provided. The cancer center had a nurse navigator named Joanne who was, by all accounts, wonderful. Joanne returned every call Eleanor placed within twenty-four hours, knew her case, and was substantively helpful. Joanne's panel was approximately three hundred and fifty patients. Joanne could not be the operating system; Joanne could be a piece of it that the patient could occasionally call into.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is healthcare in the United States in 2026 for any patient with a moderately or seriously complex care journey, and it is the area of patient experience where the gap between what the system says it provides and what patients actually experience is widest. The clinical care, on the whole, is good. The breast surgeon was excellent. The medical oncologist was thoughtful. The radiation oncologist explained things carefully. The pathologist was a board-certified pathologist with twenty years of experience. The system that was supposed to coordinate among all these excellent people, route Eleanor to the right place at the right time, make sure no referrals fell into cracks, surface results to her in time and with explanation, manage prior authorizations before they delayed her treatment, and reduce the cognitive load of being a cancer patient who is also still trying to live a life, was a sticky note, an envelope, a spreadsheet, a wonderful but overcommitted nurse navigator, and a six-portal patchwork. The math, as a system-design problem, is unforgiving. Most patients do not have a retired-project-manager spouse; many patients do not have a spouse at all; many patients have additional barriers (low health literacy, limited English proficiency, work that does not flex, transportation that is unreliable, food insecurity, caregiving responsibilities for someone else) that make navigating a complex care journey alone effectively impossible.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cost of getting care coordination wrong is not abstract. Patients who fall through coordination cracks miss appointments, delay treatment, fill prescriptions late, take wrong doses, end up in emergency departments for things that should have been handled in clinic, get readmitted after discharges that did not have coordinated follow-up, and, in the worst cases, die from things that could have been caught if someone had been actively coordinating. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on care-coordination failures and adverse outcomes includes work from the Institute of Medicine (now National Academies) reports on quality, the Joint Commission's analyses of sentinel events involving handoffs, and ongoing CMS work on care-transitions; specific figures vary --> The economic cost is substantial; the human cost is much larger. The patients most likely to fall through coordination cracks are the patients with the highest medical and social complexity, which is also the population where the cost of falling through is highest. The math compounds in the wrong direction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of care-coordination products tried to address this with three approaches. The first wave, roughly 2010 to 2015, was care-management nurse panels supported by basic case-tracking software. The clinical evidence for high-risk care management is reasonable; the operational reality is that the workforce does not scale beyond the high-risk fraction (typically single-digit percent of any given population). <!-- TODO: verify; care-management program reach is typically focused on the highest-risk members based on cost prediction models; specific reach varies by payer and program design --> The second wave, roughly 2015 to 2020, was patient-facing portals with appointment reminders, secure messaging, and (in some products) care-plan visibility. Engagement attrition was a central problem; the patients who used the portals well were largely the patients who would have done well anyway. The third wave, starting around 2020 with acceleration through 2024, layers conversational AI on top of the data, with shapes ranging from "appointment-reminder chatbot" to "navigator that can actually talk through what is happening" to (most recently) "longitudinal coordinator that holds the patient's whole journey in working memory and proactively surfaces what comes next." This third wave is where this recipe lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about a care-coordination assistant: a conversational AI tool that holds the patient's complex care journey in working memory across providers, episodes, and months, surfaces what comes next at the right moment, helps the patient navigate the multi-provider, multi-system, multi-portal reality of modern American healthcare, tracks referrals from order through completion, escalates when things fall behind, and acts as a longitudinal navigator that the patient can talk to in plain language. The bot is not a replacement for the human nurse navigator; it is the operating system that lets the human nurse navigator's panel actually be coordinated, frees the navigator to focus on the high-touch judgment calls, and gives the patient the day-to-day support that no human navigator panel can scale to.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that maintains a longitudinal model of the patient's active care journey across providers and time. The model includes the active care plan or plans, the active referrals (open, in-progress, completed, abandoned), the upcoming appointments across all providers, the recent results and what they mean, the open clinical questions the patient has, the prior-authorization status for relevant orders, the medication list and adherence patterns, the patient's stated preferences, and the relationships with the human care team (PCP, specialists, navigator, care manager).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical-decision tool. The bot does not diagnose, treat, or recommend medication changes. The clinical decisions are made by the patient's clinicians; the bot helps the patient navigate the consequences of those decisions and ensures the appointments, referrals, results, and authorizations actually happen in the order they need to happen.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a replacement for a nurse navigator. Recipe variations describe deployments where the bot operates parallel to a navigator panel, where the bot operates as the first-line coordinator with navigator escalation, and where the bot operates without navigator backup for lower-complexity coordination. In every variation, the bot escalates to humans when the situation calls for it. A care-coordination assistant deployed without human backup is a deployment with safety gaps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute symptom triage. The coordinator handles the journey-management work; when a patient surfaces an acute concern (a worsening symptom, a side effect that needs same-day attention, an emergency), the coordinator hands off to triage workflows or directly to emergency routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic-disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers ongoing condition management. The coordinator handles care-journey navigation (referral A is pending, your imaging is on Tuesday, your surgeon's office called); the chronic disease coach handles between-visit ongoing-condition management (how are your glucose readings, did you remember the metformin, let's talk about Tuesday's dinner). For complex patients these can be deployed together; the architectural patterns share much but the conversational shape and the data sources are different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not an FAQ bot. Recipe 11.1 covers institution-level FAQs. The coordinator's questions are patient-specific: where is my referral, what does my result mean in plain language, when does my prior auth come through, what should I do this week.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-condition product. The architecture supports multiple care journeys per patient (cancer treatment, surgical episode, pregnancy, post-stroke recovery, transplant work-up, multi-specialist chronic complexity, palliative care). Most institutional deployments target a specific high-impact journey first (oncology is a common starting point because the complexity is high and the value is unambiguous) and add additional journeys over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years, not sprints. The integration work alone, before any conversational AI, is multi-quarter (EHRs, scheduling systems, referral-management systems, results-routing systems, prior-authorization systems, multiple patient portals, telehealth platforms, lab systems). The clinical-content investment for journey-specific protocols and patient-facing communication is multi-quarter. The outcome-demonstration work is multi-year. Institutions building this expecting fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in any single conversation. The value is in the cumulative effect of catching the referral that would have fallen into a crack, surfacing the result that the patient would have found at midnight on the portal with no context, reminding about the prior auth two days before the deadline, sending the right pre-visit information for the next appointment, holding the patient's questions until the right clinician can answer them, and producing a coordinated experience out of an underlying system that is not coordinated. A coordinator evaluated on per-conversation engagement will be optimized for the wrong thing. A coordinator evaluated on referral-completion rates, time-to-first-treatment, prior-auth-cycle-time, missed-appointment rate, time-to-results-acknowledgment, patient-reported coordination experience, and downstream clinical outcomes is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Longitudinal Conversational Care Navigation Across Providers, Systems, and Time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Software For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a workflow, has been a phone-clipboard-and-fax problem for most of its history, with brief intermittent attempts to systematize it that have rarely held. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires holding, in working memory, a model of where the patient is in their journey, what is supposed to happen next, what is at risk of not happening, and who needs to do what to keep the journey on track. The model spans systems that do not talk to each other (the patient's EHR at the PCP's practice does not natively talk to the specialist's EHR which does not natively talk to the imaging center's RIS which does not natively talk to the lab's LIS which does not natively talk to the insurance company's prior-authorization system which does not natively talk to the patient portal). The model spans time scales (this morning's lab result, this afternoon's appointment, this week's referral, next month's surgery, next year's surveillance). The model spans clinical domains (a cancer patient may also have diabetes that needs ongoing management, hypertension that is getting harder to control under chemo-induced stress, anxiety that is reasonable given the situation but is also affecting adherence). The model spans practical realities (the patient cannot drive after the procedure, the patient's insurance changed mid-course, the patient's caregiver works during the appointment time the institution offered, the patient does not have a working car next Tuesday).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing nurse navigators do, when they do this well, is hold this model in their heads for each patient on their panel, supplemented by chart review and care-plan documentation. The model is most of the cognitive work; producing the actual coordination actions (calling to confirm a referral, making sure the prior auth went in, surfacing the result to the patient with explanation, scheduling the next appointment) is the easy part once the model is in place. Holding the model is the part that does not scale; a nurse navigator can hold maybe a few dozen high-complexity patients in active working memory, with periodic review of a larger panel. Beyond that, the model degrades. Beyond that, things start falling through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of care-coordination software tried to address this by digitizing the artifacts (the referral, the appointment, the order, the result) without addressing the model. EHRs added referral-tracking modules. Scheduling systems added cross-practice visibility for some institutions. Patient portals added secure messaging and result-viewing. Population-health platforms added care-gap registries. Each of these helped, marginally, with one piece of the puzzle. None of them produced the integrated model that a navigator holds in their head. The result was that nurse navigators, in 2025, were typically using the same workflow they used in 2005: a clipboard or its electronic equivalent, a phone, and an organized brain.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, the combination of large language models that can carry on a sustained, personalized conversation, a tool-using pattern that lets the LLM take actions through structured APIs, and a maturing FHIR-based integration ecosystem that makes the cross-system data accessible (still imperfectly, but more accessibly than before). A care-coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can carry the longitudinal model that the navigator carries (it has the chart, it has the active referrals, it has the appointments, it has the results, it has the prior-auth status, it has the conversation history, it has the patient's stated preferences and life-context disclosures), can engage in the kinds of timely, specific, warm conversations the navigator would have, can take the deterministic coordination actions that need to happen (sending reminders, surfacing results, escalating stalled referrals, surfacing prior-auth approvals, scheduling follow-ups), and can scale to the population that nurse navigation alone cannot reach. The LLM is not a navigator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the navigator workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "track-and-display" to "remember-engage-and-act." The coordinator's value is concentrated in three places: the longitudinal personalized engagement (turning hundreds of small touches over months into a coordinated journey experience), the cross-system orchestration (catching the referral that would have fallen into a crack between two practices, the result that would have sat in a portal for three weeks, the prior auth that would have lapsed), and the operational reach (extending effective coordination from the single-digit-percent of the population that gets nurse navigation to the broader population that needs it).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care-coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care journeys, active referrals, active care plans, upcoming appointments, recent results, current medications, prior-auth status, conversation history, stated preferences, life-context disclosures), access to a structured library of journey-specific protocols and patient-facing communication templates, and a careful set of tools for retrieving cross-system data, taking deterministic coordination actions, and escalating to human navigators or care managers when warranted.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (a question, a worry, a missed appointment), sometimes initiated by the coordinator per the journey schedule (your imaging is on Tuesday at 2 PM at the Westside Imaging Center, you should not eat after midnight Monday, and here is what to expect), sometimes triggered by a system event (a result has been finalized, a referral has been scheduled, a prior auth has been approved or denied, a clinician has updated the care plan, a previous appointment has been canceled and a rescheduling is needed), sometimes triggered by a pattern signal (a referral has been open for fourteen days without being scheduled, a recent result indicates a follow-up is needed and has not been booked, a medication that was supposed to start has not been picked up at the pharmacy).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The coordinator's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and journey introduction.** The patient is enrolled in coordination by their care team or by a journey-trigger event (a new diagnosis, a planned procedure, a discharge from a hospital admission). The first conversation introduces the coordinator, sets expectations (the coordinator is a tool deployed by the care team, not a replacement for human clinicians, and a human navigator is available for things outside the coordinator's scope), gathers patient-stated preferences (preferred check-in times, preferred channels, language preferences, names of people who are part of their support, things they want or do not want communicated to family members), and confirms the patient's understanding of what the journey is going to look like at a high level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Journey roadmap surfacing.** The coordinator helps the patient see what is coming. For a cancer journey, this might be the diagnostic phase, the staging phase, the treatment-planning phase, the active treatment phase, the surveillance phase. For a surgical episode, this might be pre-op work-up, surgery, post-op recovery, follow-up. For a pregnancy journey, this might be the trimester-by-trimester care pattern with expected appointments, screenings, and decision points. The roadmap is grounded in the institution's journey protocols, not freestyled by the LLM, and is calibrated to the patient's specific situation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral tracking and escalation.** The coordinator tracks every active referral (specialist consult, imaging, lab, procedure, therapy, social-work, behavioral health). Each referral has a state (ordered, scheduled, confirmed, in-progress, completed, canceled, abandoned). The coordinator surfaces upcoming referrals to the patient, surfaces stalled referrals (open for too long without scheduling), surfaces conflicts (overlapping appointments, infeasible logistics), and escalates to the human navigator when the system is failing the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Appointment management.** The coordinator surfaces upcoming appointments with all relevant detail (where, when, what, what to bring, what to expect, what to do beforehand, what the parking situation looks like, whether to fast, whether to bring a driver). The coordinator handles rescheduling requests within the institution's scheduling-system integration. The coordinator handles cancellation cleanup (the missing follow-up, the rescheduled prep, the prior-auth refresh).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pre-visit preparation.** Before each significant appointment, the coordinator delivers pre-visit content tailored to the visit type (questions to bring, information to know, things to think about, recent symptoms to track, paperwork to bring). The pre-visit content is drawn from the institution's reviewed library, not freestyled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Results surfacing with plain-language explanation.** Results that the patient is going to find on their own anyway (because they have access to the portal) get surfaced to the patient with plain-language explanation appropriate to the result type, with clear next steps, with appropriate caveats about the clinician's role, and with the option to ask the coordinator follow-up questions or to talk to the care team. Results with significant clinical implications are not surfaced by the bot until the responsible clinician has had the opportunity to discuss them; the coordinator works with the institution's results-routing policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization tracking and escalation.** Prior auths are a specific high-impact failure mode. The coordinator tracks the prior-auth status for relevant orders, surfaces approaching deadlines, surfaces denials with the next-step pathway (peer-to-peer review, appeal, alternative therapy), and escalates to the care team when a prior-auth issue is going to delay treatment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication-coordination support.** The coordinator surfaces new prescriptions, helps with pharmacy choice, surfaces refill needs, surfaces interactions or duplications when multiple specialists are prescribing, and escalates medication concerns to the appropriate clinician (PCP, specialist, pharmacist).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Question-holding and routing.** The coordinator holds the patient's questions and routes them to the right clinician. A patient with a question about their chemo regimen gets routed to oncology, not to the surgeon. A patient with a question about post-op pain gets routed to surgery, not to oncology. The coordinator does not invent answers; it routes the question and follows up.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-and-portal navigation.** The coordinator helps the patient navigate the multi-portal, multi-practice reality. Where to find the imaging report. How to message the surgeon. Which portal has the lab result. The patient does not need to learn six portals; they can ask the coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants and practical-logistics coordination.** Transportation to appointments. Caregiver coordination. Time-off-from-work navigation. Childcare during appointments. Food security during treatment. Financial-assistance navigation. The coordinator does not solve all of these but routes to the appropriate institutional resources (social work, community-based organizations, patient-financial-services, transportation programs).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition support.** Hospital discharge. Skilled-nursing-facility transitions. Home-health initiation. Procedure-recovery handoffs. The coordinator provides specific transition support with the structured discharge instructions, the follow-up appointment, the medication reconciliation, the warning signs to watch for, and a low-friction path back to clinical resources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-stated-preferences accommodation.** Quiet hours. Channel preferences. Topics off-limits. Names the patient prefers to use. Family members in the loop. Caregiver who should also receive certain communications (with consent). Cultural considerations. Language preferences. The coordinator respects all of these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term relationship maintenance.** Care journeys for serious conditions span months or years. The coordinator maintains the relationship, the conversation history, the stated preferences, the life-context disclosures. The coordinator is not pretending to be a friend; the coordinator is being a longitudinal-record interface that the patient can talk to in plain language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting.** The care team has visibility into the coordinator's interactions with the patient through structured reports: real-time alerts, weekly digests, monthly summaries. The coordinator's role is not to replace the care team's judgment; it is to give the care team the information they need to deploy their judgment efficiently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding when appropriate.** When the journey concludes (treatment ends, surgery recovery completes, pregnancy ends, the patient transitions out of the program for any reason), the coordinator supports a respectful close-out with structured summary delivery to the care team and a clear path back if the patient needs to re-engage.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care-Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, give it the patient's chart and a list of upcoming appointments, and have it coordinate. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical, operational, and patient-experience consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no longitudinal memory of the journey.** Without a structured longitudinal store of the active referrals, appointments, results, prior auths, and conversation history, the LLM treats each conversation as a fresh start and cannot do the cross-time work that coordination requires. The longitudinal store is the architectural primitive that distinguishes the coordinator from a stateless FAQ bot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no real-time view of cross-system state.** The patient's referral is in the EHR's referral-management module. The patient's appointment is in the scheduling system. The patient's result is in the LIS-to-EHR results pipeline. The patient's prior auth is in the payer's portal. Without tools that retrieve the current state from each system, the LLM is operating on stale or invented data. The cross-system tool layer is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when state has changed.** A referral that was open yesterday may have been scheduled today. A prior auth that was pending yesterday may have been denied today. A result that was preliminary yesterday may have been finalized today. The event-driven architecture that detects and reacts to state changes is part of the system, not the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of what to escalate.** A referral that is two days from a deadline. A result that has been sitting unread for ten days. A prior-auth denial that needs peer-to-peer review. A medication that has not been picked up. Each is a specific escalation pathway with specific institutional ownership. The escalation logic is encoded explicitly per institutional policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents clinical content when grounding is weak.** A coordinator freestyling explanations of what a CA-125 result means, what a stage-IIIA non-small-cell lung cancer typically gets, what a specific chemo regimen is for, or what a specific imaging study shows is delivering content the institution has not reviewed and has not validated. The journey-protocol RAG with strict citation grounding is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no clinical-decision-rule arithmetic.** The coordinator's role is not to make clinical decisions, but the coordinator does need to present information that is sometimes computed from structured inputs (oncotype-DX-driven recommendations, eGFR-based dosing implications, prior-auth-policy-rule-based eligibility). Where computation is required, deterministic clinical-rule tools encapsulate it; the LLM presents the result with appropriate caveats and routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to surface a result.** Results with significant clinical implications need clinician-first communication. The coordinator does not surface a new diagnosis to a patient before the clinician has had the opportunity to discuss it. The results-routing policy is institutionally specified and operationally enforced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient preferences for information disclosure.** Some patients want to see every result the moment it is finalized. Some patients prefer the clinician to summarize. Some patients have explicit family-communication preferences. The coordinator respects patient-stated preferences encoded in the longitudinal store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications for cross-provider coordination.** Coordination across providers, especially across separate organizations, raises specific HIPAA, state-privacy, and consent considerations. Some states require explicit consent for sharing certain types of information across providers (mental health, substance use, HIV, reproductive health). The audit, retention, access-control, and consent-routing logic handles each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when a coordination question is actually a clinical question.** A patient asking "should I be concerned that this referral has not happened yet?" is a coordination question. A patient asking "should I be concerned that I have new chest pain?" is a clinical question. The intent classifier and the scope discipline keep these in their proper lanes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of adversarial inputs.** Patients (or bad actors) attempting to manipulate the coordinator into bypassing scheduling restrictions, surfacing results before clinical communication, or extracting information about other patients require the input safety pipeline, the prompt-injection defense, and the per-tool authorization checks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to mental-health and substance-use crossover.** Coordination journeys for cancer patients, complex-medical patients, and post-discharge patients regularly intersect with mental-health and substance-use issues. The coordinator's scope handling for these crossovers is specific: in-scope coordination of mental-health appointments and follow-ups; out-of-scope direct mental-health support (which routes to recipe 11.8 patterns); aggressive crisis screening on every utterance; mandatory-reporting awareness; consent-gating for sharing mental-health-related information across providers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the coordination relationship should end.** Some journeys end (treatment completes; surgery heals; pregnancy concludes). Some patients improve and need less coordination. Some patients escalate to higher-acuity human-navigator support. The off-boarding logic is institutionally specified.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordinator Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety with scope filtering, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, prompt-injection defense, citation grounding, longitudinal-context loading, behavior-change-stage tracking (recipe 11.7), companion-pattern avoidance (recipe 11.8). The care coordinator adds seven structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system state aggregation as architectural primitive.** The coordinator's view of the patient is assembled from many systems (EHRs, scheduling systems, referral-management systems, lab systems, imaging systems, prior-authorization systems, pharmacy systems, telehealth platforms, multiple patient portals). The aggregation layer is not optional; it is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Event-driven state reconciliation.** State changes happen in source systems asynchronously. The coordinator detects, reconciles, and reacts to state changes (a referral moves from ordered to scheduled; a result moves from preliminary to final; a prior auth moves from pending to approved). The event-driven architecture with explicit reconciliation is part of the design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Journey-protocol-as-code with clinical-leadership ownership.** Each care journey has a structured protocol template (cancer treatment, surgical episode, pregnancy, post-stroke, transplant work-up, palliative care, post-discharge), instantiated for each patient with patient-specific values, signed by the institution's clinical leadership, version-controlled, and reviewed annually.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Referral-tracking-and-escalation as architectural primitive.** Referrals are first-class entities with state machines, deadlines, and escalation criteria. The coordinator tracks every active referral and escalates stalled ones to the human navigator team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Results-routing policy compliance as architectural primitive.** The coordinator's results-surfacing behavior is governed by the institution's results-routing policy (which results can be surfaced directly to the patient with what timing and what context, and which results require clinician-first communication). The policy is operationally enforced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization-tracking as architectural primitive.** Prior auths are tracked with state machines and deadlines. The coordinator surfaces approaching deadlines, surfaces denials with next-step pathways, and escalates prior-auth-driven treatment delays.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system-and-multi-organization consent enforcement.** Coordination across providers, especially across separate organizations, requires explicit consent for sharing certain information. The coordinator's consent posture is reviewed by counsel familiar with state-specific privacy statutes and is operationally enforced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration work is the product, more than the conversational AI.** The conversational AI is the surface; the value lives in the cross-system integration that the surface is built on top of. Institutions that underestimate the integration work and overestimate the conversational AI work end up with bots that have nothing useful to say. Most production deployments find that the integration work is two to five times the conversational-AI work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The cross-organization integration is harder than the within-organization integration.** Within a single organization, the EHR and the scheduling system and the imaging system are often (not always) integrated. Across organizations, they almost never are, and the integration patterns rely on TEFCA, Carequality, CommonWell, FHIR Bulk Data, and direct point-to-point arrangements that are still maturing. <!-- TODO: verify; the cross-organization interoperability landscape including TEFCA, Carequality, CommonWell, and direct FHIR-based exchange continues to evolve; specific data-sharing scope and uptake varies --> Multi-provider care journeys frequently span organizational boundaries, and the coordination quality depends on the cross-organization data quality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The journey-protocol curation is multi-quarter clinical work.** Each journey type (cancer treatment, surgical episode, pregnancy, etc.) needs a structured protocol with the appointment cadence, the key milestones, the expected referrals, the escalation criteria, the patient-facing content for each phase, and the institutional ownership. Most institutions discover, partway through the project, that their journey protocols exist informally in clinicians' heads and have to be made explicit, version-controlled, and signed off. This is multi-quarter clinical work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization workflows are a category of their own.** Prior auths are bureaucratically complex, payer-specific, frequently change, and are a leading cause of treatment delays. <!-- TODO: verify; the impact of prior authorization on treatment delays and patient outcomes is documented in AMA surveys, payer research, and ongoing regulatory work; specific figures vary by condition and payer --> A coordinator without prior-auth integration is missing a major lever. A coordinator with prior-auth integration that is inaccurate is worse than no integration. The integration with payer prior-auth systems is non-trivial, often requires per-payer customization, and benefits substantially from emerging FHIR-based prior-auth standards. <!-- TODO: verify; the FHIR-based prior-authorization standards including Da Vinci PAS, CRD, and DTR continue to evolve with regulatory mandates from CMS for federally-regulated payers --> 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Engagement attrition is the central operational risk, with coordination-specific drivers.** Patients who are tired (cancer fatigue, post-op recovery, depression), patients whose journey is going badly (treatment not working, complications, poor prognosis), and patients who have other competing demands on their attention may disengage. Mitigation: relationship-quality engineering; gentle re-engagement after rough sessions; per-cohort attrition monitoring; channel diversity; explicit acknowledgment that engagement intensity should adapt to patient state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are significant.** Care-journey navigation is harder for patients with limited English proficiency, lower health literacy, or healthcare-system unfamiliarity. The coordinator's value is highest precisely for these patients, and the coordinator has to be designed to serve them. Multi-language deployment, plain-language content review, low-literacy-friendly UI patterns, and cultural-context awareness are not optional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants integration is part of the coordination reality.** Transportation, caregiving, time-off, childcare, food security, and financial pressure are real factors in journey adherence. The coordinator surfaces social-determinants-relevant resources where the institution has them, escalates social-work needs to the appropriate team, and adapts recommendations to the patient's stated constraints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mental-health comorbidity is common in serious-journey populations.** Cancer patients, post-stroke patients, transplant candidates, and patients in palliative care have high rates of comorbid depression and anxiety. The coordinator's scope handling for mental-health crossover is specific: coordination tasks (scheduling psychiatry, managing antidepressant refills, surfacing therapy referrals) are in scope; in-the-moment mental-health support routes to the recipe-11.8 pathway; crisis screening is continuous on every utterance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The relationship to the human navigator is architectural and operational.** The coordinator is deployed alongside the human navigator team, not in place of it. The handoff patterns (warm vs. async, asynchronous-update vs. synchronous-takeover, navigator-initiated-takeback) are designed jointly with the navigator team. The navigator's tooling for reviewing the coordinator's interactions, taking over conversations, and providing feedback into protocol revision is part of the deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient consent and ongoing-consent posture is more complex than in single-condition bots.** The patient has consented to coordination as part of their care plan, but consent for cross-organization sharing, for mental-health-information sharing, for substance-use-information sharing, for sharing with caregivers, and for opting out of specific categories is granular. The institutional consent posture is reviewed by legal and compliance teams and is operationally enforced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Health-system-specific constraints often dominate the design.** A coordinator deployed at a large integrated delivery network has different constraints from one deployed at an independent oncology practice from one deployed at a payer running a population-health program. The deployment context drives most of the architectural calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is harder than it looks.** Engaged patients are not a random sample. Patients in journeys where the coordinator was deployed are not necessarily comparable to patients in journeys where it was not. Coordination outcomes (referral completion, time-to-treatment, missed-appointment rate, prior-auth-cycle time) are easier to attribute than clinical outcomes (treatment-effect size, survival, readmission). Mitigation: matched-cohort or quasi-experimental analysis; recognition that observational correlation is suggestive rather than causal; long-time-horizon commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure exists for missed coordination.** A coordinator that fails to surface a referral, fails to surface a result, or fails to escalate a stalled prior auth and the patient is subsequently harmed by the delay is a foreseeable liability exposure. Mitigation: false-negative-rate monitoring on coordination-task-completion; sampled review with the human navigator team; documented institutional ownership; institutional malpractice carrier involvement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based interoperability is more usable than it was, but is still imperfect.** The FHIR standard, particularly with the US Core profile and the various IGs (Da Vinci, US Core, USCDI alignment), is the foundation for cross-system data access. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR adoption patterns including US Core, Da Vinci, and ONC certification requirements continue to evolve; specific implementation maturity varies by vendor and use case --> Most major EHRs expose FHIR APIs at varying levels of completeness; patient-access APIs (for patient-authorized data sharing) are more uniform than provider-to-provider APIs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA is the emerging U.S. framework for cross-organization exchange.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement designates Qualified Health Information Networks (QHINs) that connect organizations across the existing networks (Carequality, CommonWell, eHealth Exchange). <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has continued to mature with QHIN designations and the Recognized Coordinating Entity oversight; specific reach and use-case scope continues to expand --> Care coordination across organizational boundaries increasingly relies on TEFCA-mediated exchange.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-access FHIR APIs are the patient-facing data foundation.** ONC's certification requirements and CMS's Interoperability and Patient Access rule require patient-facing FHIR APIs at most certified EHRs and at federally-regulated payers. <!-- TODO: verify; ONC and CMS interoperability rules including the ONC Cures Act Final Rule and the CMS Interoperability and Patient Access rule continue to evolve; specific scope and effective dates vary --> The patient-mediated exchange (where the patient authorizes the coordinator to pull their data from each provider) is increasingly the practical pattern for cross-organization journeys.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle care-coordination work well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps to coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve cross-system data, take coordination actions, escalate to humans, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human-navigator deployment is the dominant pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: the coordinator handles routine coordination at population scale, with the human navigator team focused on the high-complexity cases, the escalations, and the warm-handoff conversations. The economics work because the coordinator extends the navigator team's reach without replacing them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive for coordination programs.** Studies of nurse-navigation programs, patient-navigation programs, and digitally-augmented coordination programs have shown improvements in treatment completion, time-to-treatment, satisfaction, and (in some studies) survival for cancer patients and other complex-journey populations. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for navigation programs in cancer care includes work from the Patient Navigation Research Program (PNRP) and others, with effect sizes varying by population and program design --> Digital-augmentation evidence is more recent and continues to grow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some journeys.** Several vendors offer journey-specific patient-navigation products at major-health-system scale, particularly for oncology, surgery, and post-discharge transitions. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for journey-specific protocols and (sometimes) for the navigator workforce, and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are particularly salient for coordination.** The patients with the highest unmet coordination needs are often the patients with the most barriers to engaging with digital tools. <!-- TODO: verify; disparities in care-coordination outcomes by race, ethnicity, language, and socioeconomic status are documented in studies of cancer-care navigation and similar programs; specific findings vary --> Per-cohort monitoring with equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
